## Infrastructure

### Transportation

#### Roads and Highways

Culpeper is well-connected by road. Major highways serving the town include [U.S. Route 15 Business](/U.S._Route_15_Business_(Culpeper,_Virginia)), [U.S. Route 29 Business](/U.S._Route_29_Business_(Culpeper,_Virginia)), [U.S. Route 522](/U.S._Route_522_in_Virginia), [Virginia State Route 3](/Virginia_State_Route_3), and [Virginia State Route 229](/Virginia_State_Route_229). The main arteries, [U.S. Route 15](/U.S._Route_15_in_Virginia) and [U.S. Route 29](/U.S._Route_29_in_Virginia), skirt the southeastern edge of town. The business routes and US 522 converge downtown, following Main Street. US 29 heads southwest towards [Charlottesville](/ Charlottesville,_Virginia) and [Interstate 64](/Interstate_64_in_Virginia), while US 15 offers connections south to [Orange](/Orange,_Virginia) and [Gordonsville](/Gordonsville,_Virginia). Northbound, US 15 and US 29 merge, leading to [Warrenton](/Warrenton,_Virginia) and ultimately [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.). US 522 provides a route north towards [Front Royal](/Front_Royal,_Virginia), [Winchester](/Winchester,_Virginia), and [Interstate 81](/Interstate_81_in_Virginia), and south towards I-64. SR 3 extends east to [Fredericksburg](/Fredericksburg,_Virginia) and [Interstate 95](/Interstate_95_in_Virginia), while SR 229 connects north to [Rixeyville](/Rixeyville,_Virginia) and [U.S. Route 211](/U.S._Route_211).

The town manages its own street network, with the [Virginia Department of Transportation (VDOT)](/Virginia_Department_of_Transportation) overseeing maintenance and safety improvements on primary and secondary routes throughout the county. &#91;39&#93;

#### Rail

[Amtrak](/Amtrak) provides passenger rail service at the [Culpeper Station](/Culpeper_(Amtrak_station)), code CLP. Daily service is offered on the [Cardinal](/Cardinal_(train)), [Northeast Regional](/Northeast_Regional), and [Crescent](/Crescent_(Amtrak)) lines, connecting passengers to destinations as far-flung as New Orleans, Chicago, Cincinnati, New York, and Boston. In fiscal year 2023, the station saw approximately 17,386 passengers board or alight. &#91;40&#93;

Freight rail also plays a role in the region's transportation network, offering vital industrial and logistical connections for local businesses. &#91;41&#93;

#### Public Transportation

Virginia Regional Transit manages public transportation within Culpeper, offering both fixed-route and demand-response bus services within the town and county. The "Culpeper Connector" provides scheduled service to key destinations within the town, while the "Culpeper Express" offers countywide curb-to-curb rides, requiring advance reservations. &#91;42&#93;

For intercity travel, the Virginia Breeze network includes a stop in Culpeper on its Piedmont Express line, connecting to [Dulles International Airport](/Dulles_International_Airport) and [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.). &#91;43&#93; Limited commuter services are also available through Academy Bus. &#91;44&#93;

#### Airport

Just east of the town lies the [Culpeper Regional Airport](/Culpeper_Regional_Airport) (FAA identifier: CJR). Its 5,000-foot runway accommodates general aviation, flight training, and business aviation. Owned and operated by Culpeper County, the airport provides hangar facilities, fueling, and maintenance services for private and corporate aircraft. &#91;45&#93;

## Economy

Culpeper's economic landscape is a blend of retail, healthcare, government services, and a growing technology sector. The presence of the Library of Congress’s Packard Campus for Audio-Visual Conservation, a significant federal facility located just outside the town limits, is a notable economic driver. &#91;46&#93; Retail centers, such as the Culpeper Colonnade, also contribute substantially to local employment. &#91;47&#93;

### Technology

The technology sector in Culpeper has seen considerable growth, bolstered by enhancements in broadband infrastructure and local government initiatives designed to foster digital innovation. &#91;48&#93;

In 2022, Amazon Web Services (AWS), through its subsidiary Marvell Developments, acquired land in Culpeper for the future construction of data centers. &#91;49&#93; This announcement raised concerns among residents regarding the potential environmental impact and the alteration of the town's characteristic rural atmosphere. &#91;50&#93; Public meetings and protests were organized, with citizens voicing opposition to issues such as noise, light pollution, and the strain on public utilities. &#91;citation needed&#93;

Despite public apprehension, the Culpeper County Board of Supervisors approved the necessary zoning changes for the project. &#91;51&#93; As of 2025, construction has not yet commenced.

