## Arts and Culture

Culpeper offers a vibrant arts and cultural scene, particularly concentrated in its downtown area. Culpeper Renaissance, Inc., a dedicated nonprofit, spearheads public art initiatives, including the Culpeper Downtown Walls Mural Program. These murals bring life to the streets, depicting local history and figures, such as "The Surveyor," a portrait of George Washington, and "The Trailblazers," celebrating African American community leaders. This program even extended in 2024 to include painted utility boxes throughout the historic district. &#91;56&#93;&#91;57&#93;

The Pitts Theatre, an Art Deco gem constructed in the late 1930s, reopened as a performing arts venue in 2013 but unfortunately ceased operations again in 2016. Its striking facade, however, remains preserved. &#91;58&#93;

For film enthusiasts, the Library of Congress Packard Campus for Audio‑Visual Conservation, situated just outside town, hosts free public film screenings. &#91;59&#93;&#91;60&#93;

Annual events contribute to the town's lively atmosphere. Culpeperpalooza, a music and vendor festival held each April at Mountain Run Winery, is a popular draw. The 2025 event featured a diverse lineup of bands and supported regional nonprofits. &#91;61&#93; The downtown district also hosts regular farmers’ markets and concerts, fostering a strong sense of community. &#91;62&#93;

The Museum of Culpeper History, housed in the town's historic train depot, offers engaging exhibits and tours that delve into the region's rich past, from its colonial beginnings to its Civil War significance. &#91;63&#93; Other historical sites, such as the Burgandine House and the Culpeper Battlefields State Park, further enrich the town's historical narrative. &#91;64&#93;

