## Sports

Culpeper offers a wide array of organized sports, catering to youth leagues, summer collegiate baseball, and regional tournaments.

The Culpeper County Parks & Recreation department manages both youth and adult sports programs, utilizing facilities like the Culpeper Sports Complex and the Fieldhouse. Offerings include baseball, softball, soccer, football, rugby, basketball, volleyball, pickleball, and cheerleading, with clinics and youth camps available year-round. &#91;65&#93;&#91;66&#93;

The Culpeper Sports Complex, inaugurated in 2006, attracts over 350,000 visitors annually. It features multiple athletic fields for soccer, football, little league baseball, softball, and lacrosse. In 2022, the installation of LED lighting enhanced evening usability across 14 athletic fields. &#91;66&#93;

Youth football and cheerleading are organized recreationally by the Culpeper Football Association (CFA), which has grown significantly since its inception in 2004, expanding from approximately 250 participants to over 700 in subsequent years. &#91;67&#93;

At the high school level, the Culpeper County High School athletic teams, known as the Blue Devils, compete in basketball, football, baseball, volleyball, soccer, softball, wrestling, lacrosse, and other sports within the Virginia High School League’s Battlefield District (Class 3). The basketball team consistently reaches postseason play, including appearances in the Class 3 Region B tournament. &#91;68&#93;&#91;69&#93;

In the realm of summer collegiate baseball, the Culpeper Cavaliers joined the Valley Baseball League in 2023. This league, sanctioned by the NCAA and supported by Major League Baseball, showcases college-level athletes competing across the Shenandoah Valley region. &#91;70&#93;&#91;71&#93;

Recreational sports are also supported by facilities such as the PATH Recreation & Fitness Center (Fieldhouse) and the Culpeper Recreation Club. The Fieldhouse offers indoor courts for basketball, volleyball, and pickleball, as well as batting cages. &#91;72&#93; The Culpeper Recreation Club features a pool and courts for tennis, volleyball, baseball, and soccer, and hosts a summer swim team known as the Barnstormers. &#91;73&#93;

## Media

### Print Publications

The [Culpeper Star-Exponent](/Culpeper_Star-Exponent) is a long-standing newspaper, tracing its origins back to 1881 as the *Culpeper Exponent* before merging with the *Virginia Star* in 1953. As of 2023, it is published three times a week—Tuesdays, Thursdays, and Saturdays—in a broadsheet format and is owned by [Lee Enterprises](/Lee_Enterprises). A Lee Enterprises annual filing reported a print circulation of approximately 2,986 daily and 2,917 on Sundays prior to the change in publication frequency. &#91;74&#93;

Another significant publication is the [Culpeper Times](/Culpeper_Times), a weekly tabloid established in 1889. Owned by Rappahannock Media LLC, it boasts a print circulation of around 5,000 copies and is also available digitally through the InsideNoVa platform. &#91;76&#93;

### Broadcast Media

Local radio is well-represented. [WJMA](/WJMA) (103.1 FM), a country music station licensed to Culpeper, has been operated by Piedmont Communications since its debut on December 4, 1971. &#91;77&#93; [WCVA](/WCVA_(AM)) (1490 AM / 95.3 FM), which broadcasts classic hits, first went on the air in 1949, also under Piedmont Communications ownership. &#91;78&#93; Additionally, [WVCV](/WVCV) (1340 AM), though licensed to Orange, Virginia, simulcasts WJMA’s country format and serves listeners in Culpeper. &#91;79&#93;

## Notable Events

*   Culpeper served as the primary encampment site for the [Army of the Potomac](/Army_of_the_Potomac) during the winter of 1863-64, amidst the Civil War. It was from Culpeper that General [Ulysses S. Grant](/Ulysses_S._Grant) launched the [Overland Campaign](/Overland_Campaign) against General [Robert E. Lee](/Robert_E._Lee)'s [Army of Northern Virginia](/Army_of_Northern_Virginia).

*   During the 1960 presidential election campaign, vice presidential nominee [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson) commenced his [whistle-stop campaign](/Whistle_stop_train_tour) tour of the South with a speech in Culpeper. As the train departed, Johnson famously shouted, "What did [Dick Nixon](/Richard_Nixon) ever do for Culpeper?!" a phrase that became a rallying cry for the campaign. &#91;80&#93;&#91;81&#93;

*   In 1967, the town was the scene of a one-day standoff involving members of the [American Nazi Party](/American_Nazi_Party) and law enforcement and military personnel. The confrontation arose from the group's attempt to bury their leader, [George Lincoln Rockwell](/George_Lincoln_Rockwell), in the local [National Cemetery](/Culpeper_National_Cemetery).

*   In 1995, former [Superman](/Superman_(1978_film)) star [Christopher Reeve](/Christopher_Reeve) suffered a devastating fall during a horse competition, resulting in a severe spinal injury and permanent quadriplegic paralysis. &#91;82&#93;

*   On June 14, 2025, during a [No Kings protest](/No_Kings_protests_(June_2025)) in Culpeper, a motorist drove into a crowd of demonstrators. Police reports indicated that at least one person was struck by the vehicle, though no serious injuries were confirmed at the time, and the individual was not immediately apprehended. &#91;83&#93; The incident led to the driver's arrest and brought local attention to the underlying tensions surrounding the protest movement. &#91;84&#93;

## Government and Politics

Culpeper operates under a nine-member Town Council, which includes a Mayor and eight Council Members, all elected at-large for four-year terms. &#91;85&#93; The Council appoints a Town Manager, who serves as the chief administrative officer, overseeing the town's day-to-day operations. The Town Attorney and Town Clerk are also appointed by the Council.

Regular Town Council meetings are held on the second Tuesday of each month at 7 PM in the Culpeper County Board of Supervisors Meeting Room. &#91;85&#93;

