### Political Leanings

Culpeper County, including the Town of Culpeper, has historically shown a Republican leaning in state and federal elections. The last time a Democratic presidential candidate carried the county was in 1964. &#91;87&#93; In the 2020 presidential election, approximately 62% of county voters supported Donald Trump, while about 36% supported Joe Biden. &#91;88&#93;

Culpeper is part of Virginia's 7th congressional district, represented by Democrat Eugene Vindman as of 2025. Within the Virginia General Assembly, the town is represented by Republicans in both the House of Delegates and the State Senate. &#91;89&#93;

## Education

Culpeper is served by the [Culpeper County Public Schools](/Culpeper_County_Public_Schools) district, which encompasses all public K–12 education within Culpeper County. &#91;90&#93; Within the town limits, students attend schools such as Floyd T. Binns Middle, Farmington, Sycamore Park, and Yowell Elementary. County residents outside the town attend schools including A.G. Richardson, Emerald Hill, and Pearl Sample elementary schools, along with Culpeper Middle School.

High school students have two public options: [Culpeper County High School](/Culpeper_County_High_School) or [Eastern View High School](/Eastern_View_High_School), depending on their residential zone. The Culpeper Technical Education Center (CTEC), established in 2021 adjacent to Germanna Community College’s Daniel Technology Center, provides vocational and technical programs. It offers hands-on training and industry credentials in fields such as automotive, carpentry, cybersecurity, culinary arts, healthcare, HVAC/R, EMT, and emergency services, catering to students from both high schools. &#91;91&#93;&#91;92&#93;

In addition to public education, Culpeper County is home to several private and faith-based institutions, including Culpeper Christian School and Epiphany Catholic School, which serve pre-K through high school students with religiously-based curricula and smaller class sizes. &#91;93&#93;

